==English==

===Etymology===
Greek ''[[keros]]'', wax.

===Noun===
'''ceromancy''' ''(also '''[[carromancy]]''', '''[[ceroscopy]]''')

# [[divination]] by pouring melted wax into water and interpreting the bubbles formed.

===References===
::"By Ceromancy, where, by the means of Wax dissolved into Water, thou shalt see the Figure, Poutrait and lively Representation of thy future Wife, and of her Fredin Fredaliatory Belly-thumping Blades." -- ''Urquhart tr. Rabelais Gargantua & Pantagruel iii. xxv, 1660''

::"In ceromancy, melted wax is allowed to drip into a shallow dish of cold water, and the resulting shapes are interpreted. Ceromancy was very popular in the eighteenth century, when correspondence was normally fastened with sealing wax." -- ''Complete Bk Predictions, 1983''